during that time?

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:30.950 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: We used hypnosis
on a forensic basis

00:04:30.950 --> 00:04:33.630 align:middle line:90%
typically with a witness.

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:35.960 align:middle line:84%
You know, I could tell
you lots of case stories

00:04:35.960 --> 00:04:39.480 align:middle line:84%
where maybe it wasn't a
witness, it was a victim.

00:04:39.480 --> 00:04:41.630 align:middle line:90%
Or it was a perpetrator.

00:04:41.630 --> 00:04:45.410 align:middle line:84%
But hypnosis is not
something the courts like.

00:04:45.410 --> 00:04:48.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you're going to use
hypnosis, what you use it for

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:51.920 align:middle line:84%
is to gain information,
evidence, evidence that

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:54.620 align:middle line:90%
can be independently verified.

00:04:54.620 --> 00:04:55.620 align:middle line:90%
I know you like stories.

00:04:55.620 --> 00:04:56.745 align:middle line:90%
And I love to tell stories.

00:04:56.745 --> 00:04:57.830 align:middle line:90%
So I'll give you one, OK?

00:04:57.830 --> 00:04:59.500 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, I'm
sure some great ones.

00:04:59.500 --> 00:05:00.958 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I'll give
you an example.

00:05:00.958 --> 00:05:05.890 align:middle line:84%
I had a defense attorney
and his private investigator

00:05:05.890 --> 00:05:09.430 align:middle line:84%
reach out to me and ask me if
I would conduct a lie detection

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:13.710 align:middle line:84%
test and do forensic hypnosis
on a subject in the prison

00:05:13.710 --> 00:05:17.200 align:middle line:84%
system, convicted of the
homicide of his mother.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:20.350 align:middle line:84%
Now he was convicted
through his own admission.

00:05:20.350 --> 00:05:22.840 align:middle line:84%
According to him,
he had plead guilty

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:25.330 align:middle line:84%
because they had
made a deal with him.

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:28.720 align:middle line:84%
And the deal was he
wouldn't do hard time.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:35.040 align:middle line:84%
Well, obviously, this was
a very brutal homicide.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:39.200 align:middle line:84%
There were a lot of things
that went on in this case that

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:41.720 align:middle line:84%
are questionable
by way of how it

00:05:41.720 --> 00:05:44.990 align:middle line:90%
was handled by law enforcement.

00:05:44.990 --> 00:05:48.150 align:middle line:84%
Be that as it may, when I
sat with this young man,

00:05:48.150 --> 00:05:50.230 align:middle line:84%
I asked him about his
lie detection test, which

00:05:50.230 --> 00:05:54.610 align:middle line:84%
he'd taken, and had been
used to get him to plead.

00:05:54.610 --> 00:05:58.170 align:middle line:84%
And it turned out that it was
an illegal lie detection test.

00:05:58.170 --> 00:06:01.390 align:middle line:84%
It had been administered, a
device using only two needles.

00:06:01.390 --> 00:06:04.820 align:middle line:84%
And they're not reliable,
and situational stress

00:06:04.820 --> 00:06:07.290 align:middle line:84%
and other things
can complicate that.

00:06:07.290 --> 00:06:09.580 align:middle line:90%
So I gave him the test.

00:06:09.580 --> 00:06:11.730 align:middle line:90%
He passed the test.

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:13.450 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Meaning he
was telling the truth?

00:06:13.450 --> 00:06:14.908 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: He was
telling the truth,

00:06:14.908 --> 00:06:16.360 align:middle line:84%
that he had not
killed his mother.

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:20.060 align:middle line:84%
That was the only issue relevant
to the lie detection test.

00:06:20.060 --> 00:06:22.210 align:middle line:90%
No other issues involved.

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:25.390 align:middle line:84%
So then we did
forensic hypnosis.

00:06:25.390 --> 00:06:28.895 align:middle line:84%
During the hypnosis,
I had him go back

00:06:28.895 --> 00:06:31.962 align:middle line:84%
to that evening in
question and describe

00:06:31.962 --> 00:06:33.170 align:middle line:90%
everything that had happened.

00:06:33.170 --> 00:06:34.950 align:middle line:90%
Well, he had been at a party.

00:06:34.950 --> 00:06:37.140 align:middle line:84%
And at the party,
he'd had alcohol,

00:06:37.140 --> 00:06:38.370 align:middle line:90%
he'd had some marijuana.

00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:40.100 align:middle line:90%
He'd done some drugs.

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:42.370 align:middle line:90%
And he'd left the party.

00:06:42.370 --> 00:06:43.091 align:middle line:90%
He was lit.

00:06:43.091 --> 00:06:44.340 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Not in his right mind.

00:06:44.340 --> 00:06:45.630 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: No.

00:06:45.630 --> 00:06:49.100 align:middle line:84%
On his way to his
home, he passed

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:51.510 align:middle line:90%
through a park, a public park.

00:06:51.510 --> 00:06:54.250 align:middle line:84%
And there were law
enforcement officers

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:57.950 align:middle line:84%
in the park that just pulled
in as he was coming through.

00:06:57.950 --> 00:06:59.410 align:middle line:90%
So he hid.

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:03.080 align:middle line:84%
And he watched them
search the trash in two

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:05.860 align:middle line:84%
or three different
places in the park.

00:07:05.860 --> 00:07:09.680 align:middle line:84%
Then he went home, and
there he found his mother.

00:07:09.680 --> 00:07:14.000 align:middle line:84%
She'd been beaten to
death, sexually brutalized.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.670 align:middle line:84%
And in his stupor state
he called law enforcement

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:24.260 align:middle line:84%
and then went outside and
sat down on the porch.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:26.850 align:middle line:90%
Law enforcement arrived.

00:07:26.850 --> 00:07:29.040 align:middle line:84%
His fingerprints
were over everything.

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:33.570 align:middle line:84%
He'd handled material
in the scene.

00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:36.910 align:middle line:84%
As I say, he was given
this lie detection test.

00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:38.540 align:middle line:90%
He plead out on it.

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:40.400 align:middle line:90%
He's in prison.

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:43.340 align:middle line:84%
If there's anything
out of this story that

00:07:43.340 --> 00:07:46.200 align:middle line:84%
is going to acquit
him, it is can we

00:07:46.200 --> 00:07:50.090 align:middle line:84%
verify the time in the park
that the law enforcement

00:07:50.090 --> 00:07:54.760 align:middle line:90%
officers searched that garbage?

00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:57.700 align:middle line:84%
When we look at the logs
of the police department,

00:07:57.700 --> 00:08:01.910 align:middle line:84%
we were able to identify the
officers that were there,

00:08:01.910 --> 00:08:05.780 align:middle line:84%
what time they were there,
how long they were there.

00:08:05.780 --> 00:08:09.520 align:middle line:84%
And there was no possible way he
could have committed the crime

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:12.086 align:middle line:90%
and been there to witness that.

00:08:12.086 --> 00:08:15.990 align:middle line:90%
The conviction was overturned.

00:08:15.990 --> 00:08:17.140 align:middle line:90%
He was released.

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:19.450 align:middle line:84%
And subsequently,
the real perpetrator

00:08:19.450 --> 00:08:23.160 align:middle line:90%
was identified and punished.

00:08:23.160 --> 00:08:27.280 align:middle line:84%
So what you have, the
forensic aspect of hypnosis

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:28.835 align:middle line:84%
is to gain additional
information.

00:08:28.835 --> 00:08:29.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Knowledge, right.

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:32.909 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: The victim
says, it was a big gun.

00:08:32.909 --> 00:08:35.590 align:middle line:84%
But under hypnosis they're
able to describe everything

00:08:35.590 --> 00:08:36.429 align:middle line:90%
about it.

00:08:36.429 --> 00:08:42.270 align:middle line:84%
We have so many things that
go on that we're not aware of,

00:08:42.270 --> 00:08:44.270 align:middle line:84%
that are stored in
our unconscious, that

00:08:44.270 --> 00:08:47.600 align:middle line:84%
are available to us when
we enter into these altered

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:48.550 align:middle line:90%
states.

00:08:48.550 --> 00:08:53.740 align:middle line:84%
The subliminal you asked about
wasn't designed for that.

00:08:53.740 --> 00:08:55.640 align:middle line:84%
When you have a lie
detection practice,

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:59.470 align:middle line:84%
a percentage of the
individuals you're going to see

00:08:59.470 --> 00:09:02.460 align:middle line:84%
are going to come in and
practice a countermeasure.

00:09:02.460 --> 00:09:04.340 align:middle line:84%
And when they practice
a countermeasure,

00:09:04.340 --> 00:09:06.260 align:middle line:84%
maybe they have a thumb
tack in their shoe.

00:09:06.260 --> 00:09:09.610 align:middle line:84%
Or maybe they've been told
tense all your muscles

00:09:09.610 --> 00:09:11.390 align:middle line:90%
during the relevant question.

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:12.490 align:middle line:90%
Or whatever else.

00:09:12.490 --> 00:09:15.300 align:middle line:84%
Even when you see
the countermeasure,

00:09:15.300 --> 00:09:17.000 align:middle line:90%
you're an examiner.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.190 align:middle line:84%
You're restricted to
what your charts say.

00:09:21.190 --> 00:09:21.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:09:21.690 --> 00:09:23.417 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: You could
say, look, I don't

00:09:23.417 --> 00:09:25.250 align:middle line:84%
want you moving when I
ask you the question.

00:09:25.250 --> 00:09:26.890 align:middle line:84%
But there's a limit
to how often you're

00:09:26.890 --> 00:09:29.081 align:middle line:90%
going to go on doing that.

00:09:29.081 --> 00:09:32.070 align:middle line:84%
That leads to what we
call an inconclusive.

00:09:32.070 --> 00:09:33.660 align:middle line:84%
I don't have a
chart that I can say

00:09:33.660 --> 00:09:36.440 align:middle line:84%
you're deceptive or
non-deceptive in.

00:09:36.440 --> 00:09:38.410 align:middle line:84%
You can also have the
innocent individual

00:09:38.410 --> 00:09:41.110 align:middle line:84%
that is just so
terrified that you're

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:43.160 align:middle line:84%
going to point at them
that they bring so

00:09:43.160 --> 00:09:46.760 align:middle line:84%
much situational
stress to the scenario

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:49.820 align:middle line:84%
that you can have
an inconclusive.

00:09:49.820 --> 00:09:52.080 align:middle line:84%
So the whole idea
behind the subliminal

00:09:52.080 --> 00:09:55.470 align:middle line:84%
was I had heard the LA
Police Department had indeed

00:09:55.470 --> 00:10:01.470 align:middle line:84%
used a subliminal in preparation
for the '84 Olympics,

00:10:01.470 --> 00:10:04.560 align:middle line:84%
in case there were a
terrorist abduction scenario.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:06.280 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Now, explain
the subliminal

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:07.530 align:middle line:90%
so people can know what it is.

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:12.060 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: OK, well we're talking
about an audio message, set

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:16.300 align:middle line:84%
of messages, that are
masked in such a way

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:19.780 align:middle line:84%
that you consciously
don't recognize them

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:20.930 align:middle line:90%
for what they are.

00:10:20.930 --> 00:10:22.970 align:middle line:90%
You don't discern them.

00:10:22.970 --> 00:10:26.500 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you catch what sounds
like a voice somewhere,

00:10:26.500 --> 00:10:31.100 align:middle line:84%
but it's masked in what we think
of as maybe white noise, which

00:10:31.100 --> 00:10:34.102 align:middle line:84%
would be the sound of--
well pink noise is going

00:10:34.102 --> 00:10:35.810 align:middle line:84%
to be your furnace,
your air conditioner.

00:10:35.810 --> 00:10:37.690 align:middle line:90%
White noise, the ocean.

00:10:37.690 --> 00:10:40.340 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, OK.

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:44.780 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Think of it this way,
a frequency on a blackboard

00:10:44.780 --> 00:10:46.480 align:middle line:90%
might be a line.

00:10:46.480 --> 00:10:48.460 align:middle line:90%
So I have lines that move.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:50.230 align:middle line:84%
And these are
different frequencies.

00:10:50.230 --> 00:10:52.140 align:middle line:84%
You know that from
your audio/video work.

00:10:52.140 --> 00:10:53.139 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, yes, yes.

00:10:53.139 --> 00:10:56.240 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: If I take a piece of
chalk and I turn it sideways

00:10:56.240 --> 00:11:01.520 align:middle line:84%
and I run it down a blackboard,
over it like this, over writing

00:11:01.520 --> 00:11:03.650 align:middle line:84%
that's underneath
it, I can cover

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:05.510 align:middle line:84%
the writing that's
underneath it.

00:11:05.510 --> 00:11:07.570 align:middle line:84%
Or I might have to
get right up on top

00:11:07.570 --> 00:11:10.270 align:middle line:84%
to see if I can discern
what that writing is.

00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:12.420 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: OK, well,
properly done,

00:11:12.420 --> 00:11:15.540 align:middle line:84%
an audio subliminal
messages is recoverable.

00:11:15.540 --> 00:11:16.170 align:middle line:90%
It's there.

00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:17.135 align:middle line:90%
It's not hidden.

00:11:17.135 --> 00:11:20.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a different
track, completely.

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.240 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: You know, it
doesn't even necessarily

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:23.980 align:middle line:90%
need to be on a different track.

00:11:23.980 --> 00:11:25.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, really?

00:11:25.110 --> 00:11:26.944 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: In my
book, I tell you how

00:11:26.944 --> 00:11:28.110 align:middle line:90%
to make your own subliminal.

00:11:28.110 --> 00:11:28.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:11:28.930 --> 00:11:31.138 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And one of the
things that I tell you to do

00:11:31.138 --> 00:11:32.900 align:middle line:84%
is take advantage of
the audio illusion.

00:11:32.900 --> 00:11:36.480 align:middle line:84%
You can simply take
positive messages.

00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:40.640 align:middle line:84%
We all want affirmations
because if we use affirmation,

00:11:40.640 --> 00:11:45.450 align:middle line:84%
the evidence is strong that
they can empower us to overcome

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:47.490 align:middle line:84%
all kinds of things,
from addictions

00:11:47.490 --> 00:11:49.560 align:middle line:90%
to self imposed limitations.

00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.710 align:middle line:84%
But the problem
with affirmations

00:11:51.710 --> 00:11:53.730 align:middle line:84%
is they come from
the outside in.

00:11:53.730 --> 00:11:56.900 align:middle line:84%
So you know that
affirmation, I am good.

00:11:56.900 --> 00:11:57.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:11:57.580 --> 00:11:58.955 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And
pretty quick, maybe

00:11:58.955 --> 00:12:02.830 align:middle line:84%
my sentry, conscious
sentry says, really?

00:12:02.830 --> 00:12:04.110 align:middle line:90%
Good at what?

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:06.220 align:middle line:90%
Do you remember when?

00:12:06.220 --> 00:12:09.400 align:middle line:84%
So you begin to get this
mitigation coming back

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:13.410 align:middle line:84%
that undermines, undercuts
the power of that affirmation.

00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:15.570 align:middle line:84%
So look, let's assume
that you wanted

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:19.000 align:middle line:84%
to create some
positive affirmations.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.970 align:middle line:84%
You want to be more
confident about something.

00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:27.780 align:middle line:84%
Myself, years ago, terror over
the idea of public speaking.

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:28.860 align:middle line:90%
Another quick story.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:29.470 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:30.030 align:middle line:90%
Really?

00:12:30.030 --> 00:12:31.955 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Friend of mine,
University of Utah--

00:12:31.955 --> 00:12:33.230 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You just got
off a stage here.

00:12:33.230 --> 00:12:33.851 align:middle line:90%
So, yeah?

00:12:33.851 --> 00:12:35.350 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Professor
William Guillory

00:12:35.350 --> 00:12:37.220 align:middle line:84%
said to me years ago,
he said, Eldon, I'd

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:40.020 align:middle line:84%
like you to share your
research at the prison

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:43.540 align:middle line:90%
system with my honors class.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:44.670 align:middle line:90%
I said, well yeah, great.

00:12:44.670 --> 00:12:46.386 align:middle line:90%
I'd love to do that.

00:12:46.386 --> 00:12:48.350 align:middle line:90%
When are you meeting, and where?

00:12:48.350 --> 00:12:51.440 align:middle line:84%
And I was great until
he said Kingsbury Hall.

00:12:51.440 --> 00:12:54.050 align:middle line:84%
Well, why are we meeting
at Kingsbury Hall, William?

00:12:54.050 --> 00:12:57.360 align:middle line:84%
Well because Black Chemists
of America are in town

00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:58.780 align:middle line:90%
and I want them all to be there.

00:12:58.780 --> 00:13:01.310 align:middle line:84%
As you know, I'm President of
the Black Chemists of America.

00:13:01.310 --> 00:13:04.160 align:middle line:84%
Well that was like some
800 or 900 chemists.

00:13:04.160 --> 00:13:06.530 align:middle line:84%
You know, an honors class
is a small group of people.

00:13:06.530 --> 00:13:07.350 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:13:07.350 --> 00:13:09.890 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So I'm not
meeting with 20 or 30 people

00:13:09.890 --> 00:13:11.496 align:middle line:90%
sitting around the chairs.

00:13:11.496 --> 00:13:13.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:13:13.950 --> 00:13:16.000 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Honestly, I
drove there that day,

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.010 align:middle line:90%
Lisa, I got out of my car.

00:13:20.010 --> 00:13:22.570 align:middle line:84%
I don't know what
my-- I was so tied up.

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:24.960 align:middle line:90%
I was shaking so much, all over.

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:28.200 align:middle line:84%
I took my coat off, put
my jacket inside the car,

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:30.970 align:middle line:84%
took the sleeves of
my long sleeve shirt,

00:13:30.970 --> 00:13:33.060 align:middle line:90%
went around my tire like this.

00:13:33.060 --> 00:13:36.130 align:middle line:84%
So it would support a
story I had a flat tire

00:13:36.130 --> 00:13:37.290 align:middle line:90%
and couldn't make it.

00:13:37.290 --> 00:13:38.710 align:middle line:90%
And I drove away.

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:40.240 align:middle line:90%
And that's the honest truth.

00:13:40.240 --> 00:13:42.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:13:42.520 --> 00:13:46.520 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: As serendipity,
synchronicity,

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:50.900 align:middle line:84%
or what you would have
it, has it maybe a month,

00:13:50.900 --> 00:13:54.280 align:middle line:84%
six weeks later, I
had an entertainer

00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:58.490 align:middle line:84%
ask me to create something
for performance anxiety.

00:13:58.490 --> 00:13:59.850 align:middle line:90%
So I created a program.

00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:03.310 align:middle line:84%
And the way we do this, you
choose a mutually exclusive

00:14:03.310 --> 00:14:07.200 align:middle line:84%
profile to the
profile that-- say

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:10.740 align:middle line:84%
my profile of absolute
terror about public speaking.

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:13.750 align:middle line:84%
What would it be if I was
just completely confident

00:14:13.750 --> 00:14:15.024 align:middle line:90%
about speaking?

00:14:15.024 --> 00:14:15.940 align:middle line:90%
So that's what you do.

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:18.220 align:middle line:84%
Everything is all
positive, all right?

00:14:18.220 --> 00:14:21.810 align:middle line:84%
So I created the profile,
mixed in this program.

00:14:21.810 --> 00:14:24.030 align:middle line:84%
And the way we did it
was, you know, you just

00:14:24.030 --> 00:14:26.740 align:middle line:90%
simply use the audio illusion.

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:30.600 align:middle line:84%
You put it on top of the
waves so that you can hear it,

00:14:30.600 --> 00:14:33.260 align:middle line:84%
and then you put some
music over the top of that.

00:14:33.260 --> 00:14:36.600 align:middle line:84%
The music comes in and you
don't hear words anymore.

00:14:36.600 --> 00:14:39.185 align:middle line:84%
It's a function of how
we process information.

00:14:39.185 --> 00:14:39.890 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:14:39.890 --> 00:14:41.640 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: We can get into
that maybe in a minute.

00:14:41.640 --> 00:14:42.160 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:14:42.160 --> 00:14:43.660 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But to
continue the story,

00:14:43.660 --> 00:14:48.720 align:middle line:84%
so I grabbed this program,
this audio program.

00:14:48.720 --> 00:14:54.222 align:middle line:84%
And as it was, that
weekend I had reservations

00:14:54.222 --> 00:14:56.290 align:middle line:90%
at a cabin in a national park.

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:56.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:14:56.790 --> 00:14:59.560 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So I raced down
there, got in late, thought,

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:02.270 align:middle line:84%
I'd better play this
program before I ship it

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:04.700 align:middle line:84%
off on Monday to
this entertainer.

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:08.160 align:middle line:84%
So I put it on the
stereo and I sat back.

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:12.610 align:middle line:84%
And I was going through some
notes and I fell asleep.

00:15:12.610 --> 00:15:14.850 align:middle line:90%
And I had a dream.

00:15:14.850 --> 00:15:16.525 align:middle line:90%
And in the dream--

00:15:16.525 --> 00:15:17.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You created
this program?

00:15:17.900 --> 00:15:21.060 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --a real
life revivification

00:15:21.060 --> 00:15:25.230 align:middle line:84%
of an experience I
had had as a child.

00:15:25.230 --> 00:15:27.110 align:middle line:90%
I wanted to be a singer.

00:15:27.110 --> 00:15:29.550 align:middle line:84%
I was going to be
a Wayne Newton.

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:31.990 align:middle line:84%
I'd watched, you
know, "Hit Parade."

00:15:31.990 --> 00:15:33.510 align:middle line:90%
I'm dating myself.

00:15:33.510 --> 00:15:35.380 align:middle line:90%
I would learn the music.

00:15:35.380 --> 00:15:37.620 align:middle line:84%
And then I'd sing it
over and over again.

00:15:37.620 --> 00:15:40.780 align:middle line:84%
Well I'd learned this
song, "Vaya con Dios."

00:15:40.780 --> 00:15:42.740 align:middle line:90%
And I sung it and sung it.

00:15:42.740 --> 00:15:45.400 align:middle line:84%
Well we were at a family
reunion up in Wyoming.

00:15:45.400 --> 00:15:48.340 align:middle line:84%
And my mother's side of the
family, very white collar.

00:15:48.340 --> 00:15:51.740 align:middle line:84%
My father's side,
very blue color.

00:15:51.740 --> 00:15:53.630 align:middle line:84%
And they didn't
always get along.

00:15:53.630 --> 00:15:57.660 align:middle line:84%
So there's about to
be this disagreement

00:15:57.660 --> 00:15:59.990 align:middle line:84%
when my mother puts me out
in the middle of the floor

00:15:59.990 --> 00:16:03.080 align:middle line:84%
and says something
like, my son sings.

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:07.632 align:middle line:84%
Well here are these austere
adults in this huge room,

00:16:07.632 --> 00:16:08.942 align:middle line:90%
and I'm terrified.

00:16:08.942 --> 00:16:11.270 align:middle line:90%
And my voice breaks up.

00:16:11.270 --> 00:16:14.690 align:middle line:84%
And, you know, I run out
of the room in tears.

00:16:14.690 --> 00:16:17.410 align:middle line:84%
And I can-- you know,
I had the dream.

00:16:17.410 --> 00:16:19.830 align:middle line:84%
I sit straight up in bed--
my mother's crossed over

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:23.200 align:middle line:84%
at that point-- and I look
up, thanks, Mom, thanks.

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:27.380 align:middle line:84%
And I know where the fear came
from about public speaking.

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:29.930 align:middle line:90%
I had that terror grip me.

00:16:29.930 --> 00:16:32.020 align:middle line:84%
But when we uncover
these kinds of things,

00:16:32.020 --> 00:16:35.265 align:middle line:84%
you know, it's kind
of like-- you know,

00:16:35.265 --> 00:16:37.792 align:middle line:84%
there's a bogey man
in your bedroom.

00:16:37.792 --> 00:16:38.750 align:middle line:90%
And we've all had that.

00:16:38.750 --> 00:16:39.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah, yeah.

00:16:39.690 --> 00:16:43.680 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And we're too scared
to get out of bed, it's dark.

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:46.860 align:middle line:84%
So we call out, mom and dad
come, throw the light on.

00:16:46.860 --> 00:16:49.960 align:middle line:84%
It's how we through our clothes
over the door or the closet,

00:16:49.960 --> 00:16:50.774 align:middle line:90%
or over the chair.

00:16:50.774 --> 00:16:52.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Something's
laying on the floor.

00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:53.106 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Right.

00:16:53.106 --> 00:16:54.970 align:middle line:84%
Now, you know, you
have your laugh.

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:55.970 align:middle line:90%
They turn the light off.

00:16:55.970 --> 00:16:57.386 align:middle line:84%
They close the
door and walk away,

00:16:57.386 --> 00:16:59.260 align:middle line:90%
the bogey man's still there.

00:16:59.260 --> 00:17:01.290 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't
have power over you

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:04.000 align:middle line:84%
anymore because you
know what it was.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:08.210 align:middle line:84%
Well see, that event, using that
performance anxiety program,

00:17:08.210 --> 00:17:10.190 align:middle line:90%
did the same thing for me.

00:17:10.190 --> 00:17:14.250 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, it was like, wow, my
own uncovering, you see.

00:17:14.250 --> 00:17:18.230 align:middle line:84%
So taking these affirmations,
and using these affirmations,

00:17:18.230 --> 00:17:20.520 align:middle line:84%
getting them from
the inside out,

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:23.230 align:middle line:84%
we don't have this conscious
sentry arguing with them.

00:17:23.230 --> 00:17:24.920 align:middle line:90%
So what, back to our story--

00:17:24.920 --> 00:17:25.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:17:25.910 --> 00:17:31.360 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --what I wanted to do
was minimize situational stress

00:17:31.360 --> 00:17:33.995 align:middle line:84%
and encourage you
to tell the truth.

00:17:33.995 --> 00:17:36.595 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And so this
is what you did

00:17:36.595 --> 00:17:38.260 align:middle line:90%
with people who were in prison?

00:17:38.260 --> 00:17:39.640 align:middle line:90%
This is what you did with--

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:42.205 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well we began--
we were using it strictly

00:17:42.205 --> 00:17:43.455 align:middle line:90%
in the lie detection scenario.

00:17:43.455 --> 00:17:44.680 align:middle line:90%
And it worked really well.

00:17:44.680 --> 00:17:46.450 align:middle line:84%
I mean, the fact
of the matter is

00:17:46.450 --> 00:17:48.180 align:middle line:84%
anyone will tell
you confessions come

00:17:48.180 --> 00:17:50.120 align:middle line:84%
in the third hour
of interrogation.

00:17:50.120 --> 00:17:53.660 align:middle line:84%
So if you're ever arrested,
you're held in somewhere,

00:17:53.660 --> 00:17:55.644 align:middle line:84%
you're going to cool your
heels for a long time

00:17:55.644 --> 00:17:57.810 align:middle line:84%
before the heavyweight comes
in and starts the guns.

00:17:57.810 --> 00:17:59.139 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I see, OK.

00:17:59.139 --> 00:18:01.120 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But
utilizing the program,

00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:04.030 align:middle line:84%
we would have deceptive
indicated charts,

00:18:04.030 --> 00:18:07.340 align:middle line:84%
and the people were
confessing right off the bat.

00:18:07.340 --> 00:18:09.330 align:middle line:84%
I almost felt like saying,
whoa, wait, hold it.

00:18:09.330 --> 00:18:11.682 align:middle line:90%
I'm paid by the hour.

00:18:11.682 --> 00:18:15.340 align:middle line:84%
But, fact of the matter
is, it worked so well

00:18:15.340 --> 00:18:17.450 align:middle line:84%
that a number of agencies
started to use it.

00:18:17.450 --> 00:18:19.120 align:middle line:84%
And then the county
attorney advised us

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:23.650 align:middle line:84%
it probably wasn't a good
idea without informed consent.

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:26.900 align:middle line:84%
But about that time, a friend
of mine at the Utah State Prison

00:18:26.900 --> 00:18:30.550 align:middle line:84%
asked me, could we use
it for rehabilitation?

00:18:30.550 --> 00:18:34.150 align:middle line:84%
Could it be used to lower
hostility and aggression?

00:18:34.150 --> 00:18:36.280 align:middle line:84%
And so we went out to
the Utah State Prison,

00:18:36.280 --> 00:18:40.500 align:middle line:84%
and we ran the first of its
kind, double blind study

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:41.700 align:middle line:90%
in a prison system--

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:42.250 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:45.020 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --with
real tight protocols.

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:47.950 align:middle line:90%
And we employed the technology.

00:18:47.950 --> 00:18:52.781 align:middle line:84%
And it was so successful that
the prison system cloned it

00:18:52.781 --> 00:18:54.155 align:middle line:84%
throughout their
entire facility.

00:18:54.155 --> 00:18:56.390 align:middle line:84%
And other prison
systems adapted it.

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:58.910 align:middle line:84%
In fact, it hasn't
been a month ago

00:18:58.910 --> 00:19:00.790 align:middle line:84%
I was doing a radio
interview, and the woman

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:05.020 align:middle line:84%
that was talking to me asked
me about the prison systems.

00:19:05.020 --> 00:19:06.950 align:middle line:84%
And she's, you know,
I was at Chowchilla

00:19:06.950 --> 00:19:08.360 align:middle line:90%
when we copied it there.

00:19:08.360 --> 00:19:10.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness!

00:19:10.620 --> 00:19:13.410 align:middle line:84%
So this was a
subliminal program that

00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:15.820 align:middle line:84%
reduced the recidivity
rate of the--

00:19:15.820 --> 00:19:18.120 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: The program was
designed-- see what we did,

00:19:18.120 --> 00:19:19.600 align:middle line:84%
we went in the
prison system, again

00:19:19.600 --> 00:19:22.450 align:middle line:84%
we used some very sophisticated
psychometrics, including

00:19:22.450 --> 00:19:23.667 align:middle line:90%
the MMPI.

00:19:23.667 --> 00:19:24.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What's that?

00:19:24.500 --> 00:19:26.590 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: The Minnesota
Multiphasic Personality

00:19:26.590 --> 00:19:29.720 align:middle line:84%
Inventory is the big
one in psychology.

00:19:29.720 --> 00:19:30.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:19:30.220 --> 00:19:32.800 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: We used, for any
psychologist out there,

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:35.910 align:middle line:84%
we used the Fowler
lens specifically

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:38.450 align:middle line:84%
adapted for an
incarcerated environment.

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:40.580 align:middle line:84%
But when we came back
with all the data,

00:19:40.580 --> 00:19:42.210 align:middle line:90%
we didn't learn anything.

00:19:42.210 --> 00:19:43.810 align:middle line:84%
The only thing--
I mean, we knew we

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:46.500 align:middle line:84%
had high scores in self
and social alienation.

00:19:46.500 --> 00:19:49.430 align:middle line:84%
So the inmate had
low self esteem.

00:19:49.430 --> 00:19:53.950 align:middle line:84%
But he also held you in low
self regard, all of society.

00:19:53.950 --> 00:19:56.330 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to do it
to you before you do it

00:19:56.330 --> 00:20:00.550 align:middle line:84%
to me was kind of a
model to think about.

00:20:00.550 --> 00:20:03.890 align:middle line:84%
However, when we spoke with
them, I had my own epiphany.

00:20:03.890 --> 00:20:06.250 align:middle line:84%
And that was a major
life changer for me.

00:20:06.250 --> 00:20:10.090 align:middle line:84%
Because when you sat and talked
with the inmates, what I heard

00:20:10.090 --> 00:20:13.360 align:middle line:84%
was repeated stories
that went something like,

00:20:13.360 --> 00:20:16.060 align:middle line:84%
ah but for the grace
of God there go you.

00:20:16.060 --> 00:20:18.060 align:middle line:84%
I mean, listen, my
daddy was an alcoholic,

00:20:18.060 --> 00:20:19.540 align:middle line:90%
my mommy was a prostitute.

00:20:19.540 --> 00:20:23.120 align:middle line:84%
The neighbor boy main lined
me when I was eight years old.

00:20:23.120 --> 00:20:27.380 align:middle line:84%
You know, usually those stories
were totally exaggerated.

00:20:27.380 --> 00:20:28.690 align:middle line:90%
Sometimes they could be true.

00:20:28.690 --> 00:20:30.106 align:middle line:84%
But when they were
true, you could

00:20:30.106 --> 00:20:32.120 align:middle line:84%
have two siblings come
out of the same home.

00:20:32.120 --> 00:20:34.360 align:middle line:84%
One was a physician in
a teaching hospital,

00:20:34.360 --> 00:20:35.380 align:middle line:90%
and one's in the prison.

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:35.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:20:35.690 --> 00:20:37.565 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So it was a
matter of their choice.

00:20:37.565 --> 00:20:42.236 align:middle line:84%
It was how they-- when we
saw this blame function,

00:20:42.236 --> 00:20:43.360 align:middle line:90%
because that's what it was.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:47.680 align:middle line:84%
It was an ability to displace
responsibility through blame.

00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:49.260 align:middle line:90%
It's not my fault.

00:20:49.260 --> 00:20:50.910 align:middle line:90%
Ah, but for the grace of God.

00:20:50.910 --> 00:20:52.780 align:middle line:90%
Society's placed me here.

00:20:52.780 --> 00:20:54.990 align:middle line:90%
You know, I deserve better.

00:20:54.990 --> 00:20:57.970 align:middle line:84%
When we saw this
blame function, we

00:20:57.970 --> 00:21:01.400 align:middle line:84%
decided that the best way to
deal with that, the only way

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:05.040 align:middle line:84%
to deal with that,
was forgiveness.

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:08.160 align:middle line:84%
Now mind you, this is
back in the very early

00:21:08.160 --> 00:21:10.730 align:middle line:84%
'80s, before any
of the literature

00:21:10.730 --> 00:21:12.800 align:middle line:90%
that we all see today.

00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:16.062 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to have the
inmates forgive themselves.

00:21:16.062 --> 00:21:18.500 align:middle line:84%
Now there were some
folks that thought about,

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:20.777 align:middle line:84%
what kind of a
crazy idea is that?

00:21:20.777 --> 00:21:21.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, absolutely.

00:21:21.860 --> 00:21:23.276 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But you
know what we did

00:21:23.276 --> 00:21:26.790 align:middle line:84%
is we took a solid set
of positive self esteem

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:31.760 align:middle line:84%
affirmations, we locked
them up, with what today we

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:33.000 align:middle line:90%
call the forgiveness set.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:37.450 align:middle line:84%
I forgive myself, I forgive
all others, I am forgiven.

00:21:37.450 --> 00:21:40.630 align:middle line:84%
Suddenly you're
ability to displace

00:21:40.630 --> 00:21:42.630 align:middle line:84%
responsibility,
to blame, is gone.

00:21:42.630 --> 00:21:43.360 align:middle line:90%
It's just gone.

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:44.424 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That simply?

00:21:44.424 --> 00:21:45.340 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That simply.

00:21:45.340 --> 00:21:45.839 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:21:45.839 --> 00:21:48.765 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And if you then begin
to feel good about yourself,

00:21:48.765 --> 00:21:51.050 align:middle line:84%
you're positive that
you have abilities,

00:21:51.050 --> 00:21:55.280 align:middle line:84%
that you can do things, and
they come from the inside out--

00:21:55.280 --> 00:21:55.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:58.450 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --so that you don't
have that conscious sentry

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:03.300 align:middle line:84%
mitigating, undermining him
by continually attacking.

00:22:03.300 --> 00:22:05.290 align:middle line:84%
The next thing you
know, you open your eyes

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:07.380 align:middle line:90%
and say, you know, life's great.

00:22:07.380 --> 00:22:08.830 align:middle line:90%
I love living.

00:22:08.830 --> 00:22:10.410 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you
use this technology

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:12.880 align:middle line:84%
to actually reduce the amount
of repeat offenders, right?

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:14.880 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: That's right,
it interrupted recidivy.

00:22:14.880 --> 00:22:16.776 align:middle line:84%
But it lowered
hostility and aggression

00:22:16.776 --> 00:22:17.650 align:middle line:90%
in the prison system.

00:22:17.650 --> 00:22:20.070 align:middle line:90%
It increased reflectivity.

00:22:20.070 --> 00:22:23.250 align:middle line:90%
And that was the real home run.

00:22:23.250 --> 00:22:27.805 align:middle line:84%
And it was so successful
that our first study, it's

00:22:27.805 --> 00:22:28.890 align:middle line:90%
all volunteers.

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:30.875 align:middle line:84%
And it was in the youth
offenders facility,

00:22:30.875 --> 00:22:32.265 align:middle line:90%
these were first time offenders.

00:22:32.265 --> 00:22:35.781 align:middle line:90%


00:22:35.781 --> 00:22:39.380 align:middle line:84%
What we had there, with
this group of people,

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:41.280 align:middle line:84%
might have been
different somewhere else.

00:22:41.280 --> 00:22:44.234 align:middle line:84%
So we started moving
libraries out, elsewhere.

00:22:44.234 --> 00:22:45.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, there were
some inmates that

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:48.930 align:middle line:84%
weren't interested
in forgiveness.

00:22:48.930 --> 00:22:51.790 align:middle line:84%
Maybe rehabilitation,
but is there

00:22:51.790 --> 00:22:53.190 align:middle line:90%
something like body building?

00:22:53.190 --> 00:22:54.495 align:middle line:90%
Can you help me body build?

00:22:54.495 --> 00:22:55.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right, right.

00:22:55.370 --> 00:22:56.980 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Can I
build big muscles?

00:22:56.980 --> 00:22:59.590 align:middle line:84%
And so what we did,
little by little,

00:22:59.590 --> 00:23:03.800 align:middle line:84%
is we began to build additional
titles around this idea.

00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:05.510 align:middle line:90%
So you wanted to lose weight?

00:23:05.510 --> 00:23:07.560 align:middle line:84%
Fine, here's a
weight lost program.

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:08.780 align:middle line:90%
You want to body build?

00:23:08.780 --> 00:23:10.660 align:middle line:84%
Fine, here's a body
building program.

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:13.300 align:middle line:84%
But at the core of
all these issues

00:23:13.300 --> 00:23:16.680 align:middle line:84%
is this self esteem and
this forgiveness principal.

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:20.600 align:middle line:84%
I feel so strongly
about that, Lisa.

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:23.195 align:middle line:84%
Seriously, for
four or five years,

00:23:23.195 --> 00:23:25.270 align:middle line:84%
big career change
I told you for me.

00:23:25.270 --> 00:23:28.450 align:middle line:84%
Because my own
epiphany was, boy, I'm

00:23:28.450 --> 00:23:31.520 align:middle line:84%
holding a lot of hostility
and aggression in myself.

00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:33.650 align:middle line:90%
I'm blaming a lot of folks.

00:23:33.650 --> 00:23:35.010 align:middle line:90%
I'd left home early.

00:23:35.010 --> 00:23:36.900 align:middle line:90%
I blame my father for this.

00:23:36.900 --> 00:23:39.050 align:middle line:90%
I blame this.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:40.850 align:middle line:90%
I had a chip on my shoulder.

00:23:40.850 --> 00:23:43.980 align:middle line:84%
And I was angry
and I was paranoid.

00:23:43.980 --> 00:23:45.655 align:middle line:84%
And that was a
real epiphany to me

00:23:45.655 --> 00:23:48.270 align:middle line:84%
to discover that
my mentation wasn't

00:23:48.270 --> 00:23:50.445 align:middle line:90%
that much different than theirs.

00:23:50.445 --> 00:23:54.152 align:middle line:84%
I had only found a socially
acceptable way to act it out.

00:23:54.152 --> 00:23:55.485 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, in a different way.

00:23:55.485 --> 00:23:57.390 align:middle line:90%
It's the same stories--

00:23:57.390 --> 00:24:00.460 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So, as I'm
out lecturing on this,

00:24:00.460 --> 00:24:04.640 align:middle line:84%
and trying to walk my talk,
and change and practice things,

00:24:04.640 --> 00:24:08.840 align:middle line:84%
it became clear to me that
if it's that important,

00:24:08.840 --> 00:24:10.480 align:middle line:90%
it ought to be free.

00:24:10.480 --> 00:24:13.280 align:middle line:84%
And so 17 years ago I
made it available free.

00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:15.130 align:middle line:84%
It's free to this
day on my website.

00:24:15.130 --> 00:24:18.450 align:middle line:84%
Your listening audience could
go there and download it today.

00:24:18.450 --> 00:24:22.780 align:middle line:84%
And it's a program that's been
used by Fortune 500 executives,

00:24:22.780 --> 00:24:25.550 align:middle line:84%
not just inmate
populations, elite athletes.

00:24:25.550 --> 00:24:26.690 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:28.085 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: You name the gamut.

00:24:28.085 --> 00:24:30.210 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What's the name of
that particular program?

00:24:30.210 --> 00:24:31.960 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: "Forgiving
and Letting Go."

00:24:31.960 --> 00:24:33.780 align:middle line:84%
And to me, that's
the beginning place.

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:36.800 align:middle line:84%
If you want to take
control of your life,

00:24:36.800 --> 00:24:40.630 align:middle line:84%
you want to own
your own franchise,

00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:45.120 align:middle line:84%
you can't keep giving away your
power to somebody by blame.

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:46.910 align:middle line:90%
And that's what blame does.

00:24:46.910 --> 00:24:49.870 align:middle line:84%
I can't do anything about
it, it's not my fault.

00:24:49.870 --> 00:24:53.135 align:middle line:84%
And that stops you from
taking responsibility.

00:24:53.135 --> 00:24:54.510 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And taking
responsibility

00:24:54.510 --> 00:24:56.740 align:middle line:84%
is the biggest key that
you've found, right?

00:24:56.740 --> 00:24:58.360 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: It is a huge one.

00:24:58.360 --> 00:25:01.610 align:middle line:84%
But to me,
responsibility is-- I'm

00:25:01.610 --> 00:25:03.760 align:middle line:84%
going to be responsible
for everything

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:08.902 align:middle line:84%
that I have the power
to change in my life.

00:25:08.902 --> 00:25:10.860 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Not necessarily
the past, but from here

00:25:10.860 --> 00:25:11.669 align:middle line:90%
going forward?

00:25:11.669 --> 00:25:12.710 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:25:12.710 --> 00:25:15.040 align:middle line:84%
You know, what's in the
past is in the past.

00:25:15.040 --> 00:25:17.270 align:middle line:84%
But there's lots
of things that we

00:25:17.270 --> 00:25:20.630 align:middle line:84%
deal with in life
where we have choices

00:25:20.630 --> 00:25:23.460 align:middle line:90%
that we choose not to make.

00:25:23.460 --> 00:25:25.720 align:middle line:90%
So let me-- another story.

00:25:25.720 --> 00:25:26.910 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK, all right.

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:28.670 align:middle line:90%
Wait, just to wrap that one up.

00:25:28.670 --> 00:25:31.330 align:middle line:84%
You did create
forgiveness programs

00:25:31.330 --> 00:25:33.730 align:middle line:84%
in the prison systems, which
I think is an incredible--

00:25:33.730 --> 00:25:34.480 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Correct.

00:25:34.480 --> 00:25:36.605 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --incredible thing
to say and to have done.

00:25:36.605 --> 00:25:40.045 align:middle line:84%
And you impacted the youth,
and probably into generations

00:25:40.045 --> 00:25:41.890 align:middle line:84%
that you don't even
know of right now.

00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:43.970 align:middle line:84%
So that is a wonderful
thing to say.

00:25:43.970 --> 00:25:44.470 align:middle line:90%
That's a--

00:25:44.470 --> 00:25:44.810 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Thank you.

00:25:44.810 --> 00:25:46.101 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --a great thing to say.

00:25:46.101 --> 00:25:47.010 align:middle line:90%
OK, so continue on.

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:48.593 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So, all
right, we're talking

00:25:48.593 --> 00:25:51.610 align:middle line:84%
about self responsibility
and taking in all scenarios.

00:25:51.610 --> 00:25:55.600 align:middle line:84%
I moved my offices to Las
Vegas, Nevada at a point.

00:25:55.600 --> 00:25:57.950 align:middle line:84%
And I'm in Las Vegas,
and for the first time

00:25:57.950 --> 00:25:59.880 align:middle line:90%
I go to the post office.

00:25:59.880 --> 00:26:01.880 align:middle line:84%
And it's a routine I'm
going to do every day,

00:26:01.880 --> 00:26:02.900 align:middle line:90%
go to the post office.

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:07.890 align:middle line:84%
Not a big deal, I've been
doing that for years, but not

00:26:07.890 --> 00:26:09.030 align:middle line:90%
in Las Vegas.

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:12.220 align:middle line:84%
Not in this particular
post office on Pecos,

00:26:12.220 --> 00:26:15.220 align:middle line:84%
to all my friends that
might still be there.

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:17.886 align:middle line:84%
So I go to the post
office, and it's

00:26:17.886 --> 00:26:20.750 align:middle line:84%
an absolutely
hostile environment.

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:25.750 align:middle line:84%
I mean, everybody is grouchy,
nasty, it's hot, it's slow.

00:26:25.750 --> 00:26:27.750 align:middle line:90%
The clerks take too much time.

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:29.664 align:middle line:84%
And the clerks are worse
than the customers.

00:26:29.664 --> 00:26:30.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, wow.

00:26:30.330 --> 00:26:31.830 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And by
the time I walk out

00:26:31.830 --> 00:26:34.640 align:middle line:84%
of there it's like, I'm
just not going to do this.

00:26:34.640 --> 00:26:38.650 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to send my secretary
to do it, which isn't very self

00:26:38.650 --> 00:26:40.300 align:middle line:90%
responsible, is it?

00:26:40.300 --> 00:26:44.400 align:middle line:84%
So what I decided
I'd do is every day

00:26:44.400 --> 00:26:46.237 align:middle line:90%
I would go to the post office.

00:26:46.237 --> 00:26:48.320 align:middle line:84%
And instead of going there
and listen to all this,

00:26:48.320 --> 00:26:51.820 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to go in and I'm
going to be warm, cheerful.

00:26:51.820 --> 00:26:54.360 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have a
big smile on my face.

00:26:54.360 --> 00:26:56.310 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to greet everybody.

00:26:56.310 --> 00:26:59.544 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to do my best to
change this environment.

00:26:59.544 --> 00:27:01.710 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you the truth,
now, the first few days

00:27:01.710 --> 00:27:03.790 align:middle line:84%
I did that, I walked
out feeling like I

00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:07.260 align:middle line:84%
was a real oaf,
one stupid dummy.

00:27:07.260 --> 00:27:10.554 align:middle line:84%
I mean, people in
that post office,

00:27:10.554 --> 00:27:11.970 align:middle line:84%
I know there were
some that wanted

00:27:11.970 --> 00:27:16.490 align:middle line:84%
to call folks that had white
sacks to put me in, you know?

00:27:16.490 --> 00:27:20.450 align:middle line:84%
But I promise you this,
before 30 days had passed,

00:27:20.450 --> 00:27:22.240 align:middle line:84%
I could walk into
that post office

00:27:22.240 --> 00:27:23.765 align:middle line:90%
and the whole mood had changed.

00:27:23.765 --> 00:27:24.390 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:26.473 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I could walk up
to that counter, hi Doc,

00:27:26.473 --> 00:27:27.843 align:middle line:90%
how ya doing?

00:27:27.843 --> 00:27:31.550 align:middle line:84%
Everything had changed,
and that's how life works.

00:27:31.550 --> 00:27:35.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's what I mean by take
responsibility in your own life

00:27:35.500 --> 00:27:37.895 align:middle line:84%
for everything that you
have a party, or a part of.

00:27:37.895 --> 00:27:39.770 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well that you
can actually effect it,

00:27:39.770 --> 00:27:41.310 align:middle line:84%
and that you can
make a difference.

00:27:41.310 --> 00:27:41.630 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:27:41.630 --> 00:27:43.005 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that
you can do that.

00:27:43.005 --> 00:27:46.360 align:middle line:84%
So then at what point did you,
then, start to study-- you

00:27:46.360 --> 00:27:48.250 align:middle line:84%
were already studying
the mind, really,

00:27:48.250 --> 00:27:51.889 align:middle line:84%
through the investigations that
you were doing, and talking

00:27:51.889 --> 00:27:53.180 align:middle line:90%
to these inmates, and so forth.

00:27:53.180 --> 00:27:55.660 align:middle line:84%
But when did you turn
this into something

00:27:55.660 --> 00:27:59.370 align:middle line:84%
that was really useful
for positive affirmations?

00:27:59.370 --> 00:28:03.220 align:middle line:84%
Or using the mastery of the
mind to change the past, which

00:28:03.220 --> 00:28:04.490 align:middle line:90%
we were talking about earlier?

00:28:04.490 --> 00:28:07.540 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, again,
my epiphany, Lisa,

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:13.630 align:middle line:84%
was when I realized that-- and I
don't say this with any pride--

00:28:13.630 --> 00:28:18.290 align:middle line:84%
I listen to a story, and
I thought of an incident

00:28:18.290 --> 00:28:21.300 align:middle line:84%
I was in where I was
driving down the highway

00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:24.080 align:middle line:84%
and there were two people
in the ditch wrestling.

00:28:24.080 --> 00:28:26.730 align:middle line:84%
One of them was a law
enforcement officer.

00:28:26.730 --> 00:28:31.050 align:middle line:84%
I threw the brakes on,
got out of the car.

00:28:31.050 --> 00:28:34.473 align:middle line:84%
He was arresting a man,
stopping a man, who'd

00:28:34.473 --> 00:28:36.056 align:middle line:84%
attempted to commit
a burglary-- well,

00:28:36.056 --> 00:28:37.650 align:middle line:90%
he had committed the burglary.

00:28:37.650 --> 00:28:40.310 align:middle line:84%
He was fleeing the burglary
from a neighbor's home.

00:28:40.310 --> 00:28:43.200 align:middle line:90%
It was an off duty officer.

00:28:43.200 --> 00:28:48.460 align:middle line:84%
And the fellow, the perpetrator,
was a pretty fit fellow.

00:28:48.460 --> 00:28:53.150 align:middle line:90%
And he had done some damage.

00:28:53.150 --> 00:28:54.700 align:middle line:90%
And I was angry.

00:28:54.700 --> 00:28:59.570 align:middle line:84%
And when I cuffed this person,
I took the back of his cuffs

00:28:59.570 --> 00:29:02.590 align:middle line:84%
and cranked him over like
this, which would kneel you.

00:29:02.590 --> 00:29:05.180 align:middle line:90%


00:29:05.180 --> 00:29:11.480 align:middle line:84%
And what I don't like to
admit is that it felt good.

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:18.920 align:middle line:84%
And when I recognized
that I had that within me,

00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:21.640 align:middle line:84%
I realized that there
wasn't a lot of difference

00:29:21.640 --> 00:29:24.180 align:middle line:90%
between the inmate and myself.

00:29:24.180 --> 00:29:25.980 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because the
anger took over?

00:29:25.980 --> 00:29:27.770 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: The anger
had just taken over.

00:29:27.770 --> 00:29:30.270 align:middle line:90%
It was all about anger.

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:34.710 align:middle line:84%
So, again, I had found a
socially acceptable way

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:35.660 align:middle line:90%
to act out.

00:29:35.660 --> 00:29:36.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:29:36.680 --> 00:29:38.930 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Sublimation.

00:29:38.930 --> 00:29:44.860 align:middle line:84%
So, at that point in my life
I wanted to make a change.

00:29:44.860 --> 00:29:48.450 align:middle line:90%
I decided I had to change.

00:29:48.450 --> 00:29:50.950 align:middle line:84%
And I realized that
that's maybe why

00:29:50.950 --> 00:29:53.660 align:middle line:84%
I was his paranoid
and suspicious of

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:57.330 align:middle line:84%
people, as why nothing
in my life worked.

00:29:57.330 --> 00:29:58.890 align:middle line:90%
I mean, my practice worked.

00:29:58.890 --> 00:30:01.830 align:middle line:84%
I had fancy new
cars, I had property.

00:30:01.830 --> 00:30:03.950 align:middle line:84%
But my personal
life was shambles.

00:30:03.950 --> 00:30:09.240 align:middle line:84%
I mean, nothing in my
personal life worked, nothing.

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:11.320 align:middle line:90%
So I decided I needed some help.

00:30:11.320 --> 00:30:15.760 align:middle line:84%
And the tools that were
available to me, part of them

00:30:15.760 --> 00:30:17.660 align:middle line:90%
my own, from the prison system.

00:30:17.660 --> 00:30:20.890 align:middle line:84%
Part of them was a
matter of redressing

00:30:20.890 --> 00:30:25.140 align:middle line:84%
how I viewed the world, changing
the context, so that I wasn't

00:30:25.140 --> 00:30:28.150 align:middle line:84%
constantly suspicious
of everyone,

00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:33.920 align:middle line:84%
or expecting the worst from
everyone, including myself.

00:30:33.920 --> 00:30:35.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Ah.

00:30:35.650 --> 00:30:37.990 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I happen
to-- you know--

00:30:37.990 --> 00:30:42.450 align:middle line:84%
Little story, I happened to
choose a person, a counselor,

00:30:42.450 --> 00:30:45.930 align:middle line:84%
who-- I'll never forget this--
it was a big change in my life.

00:30:45.930 --> 00:30:49.370 align:middle line:84%
It was very early,
who, on a given day,

00:30:49.370 --> 00:30:52.620 align:middle line:84%
said the me, Eldon, you know,
if you're going to change,

00:30:52.620 --> 00:30:54.880 align:middle line:84%
you're going to have
to start thinking

00:30:54.880 --> 00:30:56.850 align:middle line:90%
that the universe loves you.

00:30:56.850 --> 00:30:59.760 align:middle line:84%
That the universe is going
to bring you good things.

00:30:59.760 --> 00:31:02.570 align:middle line:90%
That good is in everything.

00:31:02.570 --> 00:31:04.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Did you believe
him in the beginning?

00:31:04.720 --> 00:31:05.820 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Get out of here.

00:31:05.820 --> 00:31:06.820 align:middle line:90%
You know what I've seen?

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:08.170 align:middle line:84%
Don't tell me good's
in everything, okay.

00:31:08.170 --> 00:31:09.096 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I am sure.

00:31:09.096 --> 00:31:10.210 align:middle line:90%
Right, right.

00:31:10.210 --> 00:31:12.370 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: But she
impressed me with the idea

00:31:12.370 --> 00:31:18.140 align:middle line:84%
that if I would take every
event that occurred to me,

00:31:18.140 --> 00:31:20.930 align:middle line:84%
and I would simply put a
sentence in front of it,

00:31:20.930 --> 00:31:23.794 align:middle line:84%
it could change how I
interpreted those events.

00:31:23.794 --> 00:31:24.710 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What was that?

00:31:24.710 --> 00:31:26.460 align:middle line:10%
>>TAYLOR: And that
one sentence was,

00:31:26.460 --> 00:31:30.020 align:middle line:10%
I can't wait to see what
good comes from this.

00:31:30.020 --> 00:31:31.990 align:middle line:10%
So I said to her, I said, OK.

00:31:31.990 --> 00:31:33.100 align:middle line:10%
I will try that.

00:31:33.100 --> 00:31:34.190 align:middle line:90%
I will try that.

00:31:34.190 --> 00:31:36.160 align:middle line:90%
So I left.

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:38.460 align:middle line:84%
I left her office,
I went to my office.

00:31:38.460 --> 00:31:41.180 align:middle line:84%
My office was in a
horseshoe shaped mall.

00:31:41.180 --> 00:31:44.970 align:middle line:84%
And in the front, center of
that mall, was a restaurant.

00:31:44.970 --> 00:31:47.674 align:middle line:84%
So I had to pull my car
in between the restaurant

00:31:47.674 --> 00:31:49.590 align:middle line:84%
and the rest of the mall,
because I'm up here.

00:31:49.590 --> 00:31:50.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:31:50.090 --> 00:31:54.250 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And as I pull in, my
brand new El Dorado Biarritz

00:31:54.250 --> 00:31:57.830 align:middle line:84%
with its steel top--
brushed steel top--

00:31:57.830 --> 00:31:58.520 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:31:58.520 --> 00:32:02.890 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --out comes this
clunker car, broad sides me.

00:32:02.890 --> 00:32:03.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:07.354 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I honestly said
to myself, I cannot wait--

00:32:07.354 --> 00:32:08.020 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You did?

00:32:08.020 --> 00:32:10.450 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --to see what
good comes from this.

00:32:10.450 --> 00:32:11.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:32:11.210 --> 00:32:15.110 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And I swung open
the car door, stepped out.

00:32:15.110 --> 00:32:18.680 align:middle line:84%
The guy in this car, this
clunker that has run into me,

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:22.260 align:middle line:84%
he's wagging the finger,
accusing me of hiding my car

00:32:22.260 --> 00:32:24.777 align:middle line:90%
behind him.

00:32:24.777 --> 00:32:28.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, if I hadn't had said
to myself what I did,

00:32:28.410 --> 00:32:29.659 align:middle line:90%
kind of set that up--

00:32:29.659 --> 00:32:30.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:32.470 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --you know, the
adrenalin is apt to run in.

00:32:32.470 --> 00:32:33.011 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:32:33.011 --> 00:32:34.410 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: I could
have got upset.

00:32:34.410 --> 00:32:37.205 align:middle line:90%
Things could've taken over.

00:32:37.205 --> 00:32:41.301 align:middle line:84%
The body has two budgets,
analogous to the government.

00:32:41.301 --> 00:32:41.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:32:41.800 --> 00:32:44.760 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: There's one for
growth and one for defense.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:45.260 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:32:45.260 --> 00:32:47.530 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: When we pour
on the adrenaline,

00:32:47.530 --> 00:32:51.890 align:middle line:84%
all that cortisol,
what happens is

00:32:51.890 --> 00:32:54.970 align:middle line:84%
we shut down the
optimal operation.

00:32:54.970 --> 00:32:56.330 align:middle line:90%
We're in defense.

00:32:56.330 --> 00:32:58.610 align:middle line:84%
So the ANS, the immune,
and the endocrine,

00:32:58.610 --> 00:33:01.179 align:middle line:84%
they don't work the way
they should work, optimally.

00:33:01.179 --> 00:33:02.595 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: They go
into defense mode.

00:33:02.595 --> 00:33:04.360 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So the
pragmatist in me--

00:33:04.360 --> 00:33:07.160 align:middle line:84%
and again I'm coming back,
being left brained here now,

00:33:07.160 --> 00:33:11.200 align:middle line:84%
always analyzing everything--
the pragmatist in me

00:33:11.200 --> 00:33:12.910 align:middle line:90%
says, you knowk, that was smart.

00:33:12.910 --> 00:33:16.870 align:middle line:84%
Because I didn't have all those
chemicals pour into my system.

00:33:16.870 --> 00:33:20.600 align:middle line:84%
Instead, what happened is there
were two peace officers coming

00:33:20.600 --> 00:33:21.800 align:middle line:90%
out at that moment.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:23.630 align:middle line:90%
They saw what happened.

00:33:23.630 --> 00:33:25.810 align:middle line:84%
I ended up in a car
with one, and we

00:33:25.810 --> 00:33:29.740 align:middle line:84%
were roaring about this guy
wagging his finger at me.

00:33:29.740 --> 00:33:31.730 align:middle line:84%
And to this day, when
I share that story,

00:33:31.730 --> 00:33:33.870 align:middle line:84%
I can't help but
smile and laugh.

00:33:33.870 --> 00:33:37.862 align:middle line:84%
I don't think back to my new
car just got smashed, you see.

00:33:37.862 --> 00:33:39.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Interesting,
you think back

00:33:39.320 --> 00:33:40.569 align:middle line:90%
to that essence of the story.

00:33:40.569 --> 00:33:41.860 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's exactly right.

00:33:41.860 --> 00:33:46.530 align:middle line:84%
And that's an example of how we
can change a context and change

00:33:46.530 --> 00:33:47.030 align:middle line:90%
everything.

00:33:47.030 --> 00:33:49.279 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's interesting
though, that you changed that

00:33:49.279 --> 00:33:50.920 align:middle line:84%
through just your
analytical thinking.

00:33:50.920 --> 00:33:53.590 align:middle line:84%
You thought you needed
to insert this sentence.

00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:56.167 align:middle line:84%
And it actually changed
the chemistry of your body.

00:33:56.167 --> 00:33:57.750 align:middle line:84%
You didn't do it
through a subliminal.

00:33:57.750 --> 00:33:58.020 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: No.

00:33:58.020 --> 00:33:59.480 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You didn't do
it through hypnosis.

00:33:59.480 --> 00:33:59.850 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: No.

00:33:59.850 --> 00:34:01.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You did it through
cognitive thinking.

00:34:01.440 --> 00:34:02.398 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:34:02.398 --> 00:34:04.720 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that that
is also possible.

00:34:04.720 --> 00:34:06.750 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And not just
possible, it's probable.

00:34:06.750 --> 00:34:08.980 align:middle line:84%
You know, Friedrich
Nietzsche, who

00:34:08.980 --> 00:34:13.190 align:middle line:84%
I'm not really fond
of because I just

00:34:13.190 --> 00:34:15.870 align:middle line:84%
have a different view
of life than he did,

00:34:15.870 --> 00:34:18.050 align:middle line:84%
nevertheless, said some
pretty powerful things.

00:34:18.050 --> 00:34:22.469 align:middle line:84%
And in his essay, "Twilight,"
he asks all of us, why is it

00:34:22.469 --> 00:34:25.750 align:middle line:84%
you don't sit down and
decide what characters

00:34:25.750 --> 00:34:28.949 align:middle line:90%
you would like as who you are?

00:34:28.949 --> 00:34:31.800 align:middle line:84%
Why don't we sit down and say
I want to be an honest person?

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:34.040 align:middle line:84%
I want to be a
forthright person.

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:38.040 align:middle line:90%
I want to be a jovial person.

00:34:38.040 --> 00:34:42.460 align:middle line:84%
Why don't we create the
list of characteristics

00:34:42.460 --> 00:34:45.360 align:middle line:90%
that make up who we are?

00:34:45.360 --> 00:34:46.989 align:middle line:90%
That's a fair question.

00:34:46.989 --> 00:34:50.870 align:middle line:84%
When I went to college, I
was told certain things.

00:34:50.870 --> 00:34:54.650 align:middle line:84%
They were axiomatic supposedly,
but of course they're not.

00:34:54.650 --> 00:34:57.530 align:middle line:84%
IQ is fixed, that's
false to fact.

00:34:57.530 --> 00:34:59.000 align:middle line:90%
We can change IQ today.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:01.220 align:middle line:90%
And we know that, yeah.

00:35:01.220 --> 00:35:05.540 align:middle line:84%
Personality is fixed, ages
four, six, somewhere in there.

00:35:05.540 --> 00:35:07.960 align:middle line:84%
That too, is false,
false to fact.

00:35:07.960 --> 00:35:10.290 align:middle line:84%
In fact, studies
show today that one

00:35:10.290 --> 00:35:13.180 align:middle line:84%
of the best ways you
can improve your life

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:15.450 align:middle line:90%
is by changing your personality.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:17.750 align:middle line:84%
That's this list
of characteristics,

00:35:17.750 --> 00:35:19.984 align:middle line:90%
deciding the ones that you want.

00:35:19.984 --> 00:35:21.900 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You can change
from a dishonest person

00:35:21.900 --> 00:35:22.760 align:middle line:90%
to an honest person.

00:35:22.760 --> 00:35:24.370 align:middle line:84%
From an unloving person
to a loving person.

00:35:24.370 --> 00:35:26.494 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Absolutely, and
that power is within you.

00:35:26.494 --> 00:35:31.220 align:middle line:84%
But you have to understand this,
functional magnetic resonance

00:35:31.220 --> 00:35:34.240 align:middle line:84%
imaging has confirmed something
that Benjamin Libit showed us

00:35:34.240 --> 00:35:37.650 align:middle line:84%
back in the '50s that started
a whole big conversation

00:35:37.650 --> 00:35:40.210 align:middle line:84%
in universities
around the world.

00:35:40.210 --> 00:35:44.140 align:middle line:84%
Libit watched the
brain have activity

00:35:44.140 --> 00:35:48.290 align:middle line:84%
in the unconscious before the
conscious mind did anything.

00:35:48.290 --> 00:35:53.450 align:middle line:84%
His classical, cortical evoked
potential, the p300 wave,

00:35:53.450 --> 00:35:55.720 align:middle line:84%
and theorized that
the unconscious

00:35:55.720 --> 00:35:57.940 align:middle line:84%
was telling the
conscious what to do.

00:35:57.940 --> 00:36:00.770 align:middle line:84%
And of course, if that's the
case, then where is free will?

00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:04.200 align:middle line:84%
Well, today, functional
magnetic resonance imaging

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:07.580 align:middle line:84%
shows us that a technician
watching your brain

00:36:07.580 --> 00:36:11.340 align:middle line:84%
as you make a choice, as you
come to a decision, Lisa,

00:36:11.340 --> 00:36:15.880 align:middle line:84%
will know what you're going to
do 6 to 10 seconds before you

00:36:15.880 --> 00:36:17.600 align:middle line:90%
know what you're going to do.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:19.210 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: By watching the--

00:36:19.210 --> 00:36:21.820 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Your brain
makes that choice for you.

00:36:21.820 --> 00:36:23.260 align:middle line:90%
It's made for you.

00:36:23.260 --> 00:36:26.200 align:middle line:84%
You think the conscious
mind is making the decision,

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:26.930 align:middle line:90%
but it's not.

00:36:26.930 --> 00:36:28.138 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's the unconscious.

00:36:28.138 --> 00:36:30.210 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So in a sort of
way, you have to think,

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:33.380 align:middle line:84%
OK, the mind is a bit
like a biocomputer.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:37.390 align:middle line:84%
I have a friend that's a
neurosurgeon in Hilo, Hawaii,

00:36:37.390 --> 00:36:40.020 align:middle line:90%
Doctor John Turner.

00:36:40.020 --> 00:36:40.986 align:middle line:90%
He goes by Jack.

00:36:40.986 --> 00:36:43.110 align:middle line:84%
Jack and I've had lots of
conversations about this.

00:36:43.110 --> 00:36:46.080 align:middle line:84%
And Jack says, Eldon, there
is no such thing as free will.

00:36:46.080 --> 00:36:47.300 align:middle line:90%
It's all predetermined.

00:36:47.300 --> 00:36:49.360 align:middle line:84%
Everything that's going
to happen is all written,

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:50.444 align:middle line:90%
it's just going to happen.

00:36:50.444 --> 00:36:52.318 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's written in
the unconscious mind?

00:36:52.318 --> 00:36:54.570 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Well, it's written
at least there, isn't it?

00:36:54.570 --> 00:36:58.900 align:middle line:84%
If you have free will,
it's due to your ability

00:36:58.900 --> 00:37:02.400 align:middle line:84%
to change what's in here,
so that what comes out

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:05.600 align:middle line:84%
here is a choice
of your choosing.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about what's
in your-- we'll call it

00:37:08.100 --> 00:37:09.760 align:middle line:84%
a biocomputer--
we'll use Maxwell--

00:37:09.760 --> 00:37:11.130 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're unconscious mind.

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:13.810 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --we'd think about
what's in there, how much of it

00:37:13.810 --> 00:37:14.650 align:middle line:90%
is negative?

00:37:14.650 --> 00:37:17.910 align:middle line:84%
How often have you been
told, no you can't?

00:37:17.910 --> 00:37:19.760 align:middle line:84%
Don't do this,
you're too stupid.

00:37:19.760 --> 00:37:22.320 align:middle line:84%
You're not old enough,
you're not pretty enough.

00:37:22.320 --> 00:37:23.660 align:middle line:90%
You're too fat.

00:37:23.660 --> 00:37:27.110 align:middle line:84%
I mean, think about all the
negative that we're all told.

00:37:27.110 --> 00:37:28.870 align:middle line:84%
And then listen to
yourself when you

00:37:28.870 --> 00:37:31.297 align:middle line:84%
tell yourself
something positive.

00:37:31.297 --> 00:37:32.880 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's almost
like that negative

00:37:32.880 --> 00:37:35.692 align:middle line:84%
has to get out and get
purged in order to be heard,

00:37:35.692 --> 00:37:37.400 align:middle line:84%
and then it goes away
for a little while.

00:37:37.400 --> 00:37:39.360 align:middle line:84%
But how do you really
ever actually change it?

00:37:39.360 --> 00:37:40.485 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: --really go away.

00:37:40.485 --> 00:37:40.790 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I know.

00:37:40.790 --> 00:37:42.540 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: When you say
for a little while,

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:44.770 align:middle line:84%
I mean we have 50,000
thoughts a day.

00:37:44.770 --> 00:37:48.990 align:middle line:84%
But those 50,000 thoughts are
just recycling themselves.

00:37:48.990 --> 00:37:50.990 align:middle line:84%
And the only way we're
going to change them

00:37:50.990 --> 00:37:53.720 align:middle line:84%
is to introduce a new
pattern of thinking,

00:37:53.720 --> 00:37:56.190 align:middle line:90%
a new set of thoughts.

00:37:56.190 --> 00:37:59.990 align:middle line:84%
So if we decide we
want, for example,

00:37:59.990 --> 00:38:03.350 align:middle line:84%
to add some characteristic
to who we are,

00:38:03.350 --> 00:38:09.850 align:middle line:84%
we decide that today, going
forward, what characteristic?

00:38:09.850 --> 00:38:11.260 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to have good posture.

00:38:11.260 --> 00:38:11.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:38:11.760 --> 00:38:13.570 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: How am I going
to get good posture?

00:38:13.570 --> 00:38:17.450 align:middle line:84%
Well, I'm going to have to
make the decision, which

00:38:17.450 --> 00:38:19.530 align:middle line:90%
is a cognitive event.

00:38:19.530 --> 00:38:22.370 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to have to learn
what's involved in posture.

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:23.650 align:middle line:90%
What does good posture mean?

00:38:23.650 --> 00:38:27.430 align:middle line:84%
Does that involve sitting
as well as standing?

00:38:27.430 --> 00:38:30.700 align:middle line:90%
How will it impact my stride?

00:38:30.700 --> 00:38:32.420 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to do a
little bit of homework,

00:38:32.420 --> 00:38:33.870 align:middle line:90%
and that's all cognitive.

00:38:33.870 --> 00:38:34.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:38:34.370 --> 00:38:36.820 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Now, let's
assume then that I've

00:38:36.820 --> 00:38:39.000 align:middle line:90%
got a script inside my mind.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.000 align:middle line:84%
And that script somehow,
I'm not aware of.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.880 align:middle line:84%
It's like my fear
of public speaking.

00:38:44.880 --> 00:38:45.700 align:middle line:90%
It's hidden away.

00:38:45.700 --> 00:38:47.120 align:middle line:90%
It's a defense strategy.

00:38:47.120 --> 00:38:50.490 align:middle line:84%
And for a defense mechanism to
work, it has to be hidden away.

00:38:50.490 --> 00:38:52.900 align:middle line:84%
So I kind of slumped
down, because if I sat up,

00:38:52.900 --> 00:38:54.540 align:middle line:90%
the teacher called on me.

00:38:54.540 --> 00:38:57.000 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I didn't
know what it was.

00:38:57.000 --> 00:38:58.930 align:middle line:84%
And I didn't want
to be embarrassed.

00:38:58.930 --> 00:38:59.810 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:38:59.810 --> 00:39:04.580 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So we all have these
adaptations that are within us.

00:39:04.580 --> 00:39:06.650 align:middle line:84%
Well then I have to
observe my behavior.

00:39:06.650 --> 00:39:10.480 align:middle line:84%
And I have to observe
how I talk to myself.

00:39:10.480 --> 00:39:12.640 align:middle line:84%
You know, one thing that
I do-- I did it today--

00:39:12.640 --> 00:39:16.822 align:middle line:84%
I asked everybody that was
present, 1,000 people or so,

00:39:16.822 --> 00:39:19.030 align:middle line:84%
how many of you would like
to make a million dollars?

00:39:19.030 --> 00:39:21.430 align:middle line:84%
And of course every hand
goes up in the place.

00:39:21.430 --> 00:39:22.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:23.820 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: All right,
now if you want

00:39:23.820 --> 00:39:25.920 align:middle line:84%
to make a million dollars--
I didn't say win it,

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:27.564 align:middle line:84%
make it- you know
that you're going

00:39:27.564 --> 00:39:28.980 align:middle line:84%
to have to do
something different.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:30.438 align:middle line:84%
You're going to
have to go at risk.

00:39:30.438 --> 00:39:32.850 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you're going to have
to change your career.

00:39:32.850 --> 00:39:35.440 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you're going to have
to mortgage your home.

00:39:35.440 --> 00:39:37.280 align:middle line:84%
But you're going to
have to do something

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:40.560 align:middle line:84%
different to make a
million dollars, right?

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:41.144 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:39:41.144 --> 00:39:42.685 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: To begin
with, you're going

00:39:42.685 --> 00:39:45.000 align:middle line:84%
to have to believe it's
possible, because if you don't

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:48.150 align:middle line:84%
believe it's possible, it
isn't going to happen, right?

00:39:48.150 --> 00:39:50.000 align:middle line:84%
You know, they had
Bill Gates, you

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:51.899 align:middle line:84%
know he's not going to
have a problem saying,

00:39:51.899 --> 00:39:53.690 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to make a
million dollars, is he?

00:39:53.690 --> 00:39:55.320 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: He did it yesterday.

00:39:55.320 --> 00:39:58.080 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Yeah, he did
five minutes ago, OK?

00:39:58.080 --> 00:39:59.290 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:39:59.290 --> 00:40:02.099 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: So what you're going
to do, what I want you to do,

00:40:02.099 --> 00:40:04.390 align:middle line:84%
is say to yourself-- and
everybody in your audience can

00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:08.220 align:middle line:84%
do this, too-- say to yourself,
slowly and meaningfully--

00:40:08.220 --> 00:40:08.721 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:40:08.721 --> 00:40:11.136 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: --this year I'm going
to make a million dollars.

00:40:11.136 --> 00:40:13.230 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to earn a
million dollars this year.

00:40:13.230 --> 00:40:15.920 align:middle line:84%
Say it really seriously
and see how long

00:40:15.920 --> 00:40:18.170 align:middle line:84%
it takes before you
get something like,

00:40:18.170 --> 00:40:19.890 align:middle line:84%
what are you going
to do, rob a bank?

00:40:19.890 --> 00:40:20.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How?

00:40:20.500 --> 00:40:21.360 align:middle line:90%
Right, right.

00:40:21.360 --> 00:40:22.770 align:middle line:84%
That's the first thing
that came up when this year

00:40:22.770 --> 00:40:23.530 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to make
a million dollars.

00:40:23.530 --> 00:40:24.100 align:middle line:90%
Well, how?

00:40:24.100 --> 00:40:25.225 align:middle line:90%
I didn't do that last year.

00:40:25.225 --> 00:40:26.460 align:middle line:90%
So how would I-- but yeah.

00:40:26.460 --> 00:40:27.293 align:middle line:90%
It starts coming in.

00:40:27.293 --> 00:40:29.490 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And so, that
language coming back

00:40:29.490 --> 00:40:32.322 align:middle line:84%
in is telling what
you really believe.

00:40:32.322 --> 00:40:33.780 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What the
evidence is, yeah.

00:40:33.780 --> 00:40:35.360 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: If you
become mindful--

00:40:35.360 --> 00:40:37.670 align:middle line:84%
and that's the big
buzzword right now-- but

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:41.000 align:middle line:84%
if you become mindful, you pay
attention to your thoughts,

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:43.340 align:middle line:84%
without judging
those thoughts you

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:46.940 align:middle line:84%
begin to see what it is
that you truly believe.

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:49.180 align:middle line:84%
Not what you're trying
to tell yourself,

00:40:49.180 --> 00:40:51.380 align:middle line:90%
but what's really in your mind.

00:40:51.380 --> 00:40:53.510 align:middle line:84%
And as you do that,
then you can begin

00:40:53.510 --> 00:40:57.500 align:middle line:84%
to write a counter
statement to that.

00:40:57.500 --> 00:41:00.600 align:middle line:84%
So life sucks and then
you die, you know?

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:02.450 align:middle line:90%
I don't get even, I get evener.

00:41:02.450 --> 00:41:06.520 align:middle line:84%
Those are mentation
processes that

00:41:06.520 --> 00:41:09.080 align:middle line:90%
set up a way we see the world.

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:11.090 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That are stuck
in the subconscious mind.

00:41:11.090 --> 00:41:12.350 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:13.660 align:middle line:90%
And they cycle.

00:41:13.660 --> 00:41:16.580 align:middle line:84%
And so they set up
our expectation.

00:41:16.580 --> 00:41:18.136 align:middle line:84%
Our expectation
is very powerful.

00:41:18.136 --> 00:41:19.260 align:middle line:90%
Let me give you an example.

00:41:19.260 --> 00:41:20.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:41:20.230 --> 00:41:21.390 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Placebo research.

00:41:21.390 --> 00:41:21.973 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:41:21.973 --> 00:41:24.290 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: We know that if I
give you a plain white pill

00:41:24.290 --> 00:41:26.660 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be, you
know, 20% effective,

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:28.940 align:middle line:90%
plus or minus, all right?

00:41:28.940 --> 00:41:30.390 align:middle line:90%
10% to 20%.

00:41:30.390 --> 00:41:33.947 align:middle line:84%
If I put an initial on that
pill, it'll be more effective.

00:41:33.947 --> 00:41:34.780 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Any initial?

00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:36.685 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Any initial,
just put an initial.

00:41:36.685 --> 00:41:37.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:41:37.310 --> 00:41:40.570 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: If I name the pill,
it's still more effective.

00:41:40.570 --> 00:41:43.685 align:middle line:84%
If I turn it into a capsule,
it gets more effective.

00:41:43.685 --> 00:41:44.310 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:41:44.310 --> 00:41:46.270 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: If I
colorize that capsule,

00:41:46.270 --> 00:41:49.690 align:middle line:84%
and I even know what color,
it still gets more effective.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:50.190 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:41:50.190 --> 00:41:53.380 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: Now, if I put
that capsule in a fancy box,

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:54.860 align:middle line:90%
it's still more effective.

00:41:54.860 --> 00:41:56.040 align:middle line:90%
But you know what?

00:41:56.040 --> 00:42:01.400 align:middle line:84%
If I give you the injection, we
can have a placebo work as well

00:42:01.400 --> 00:42:04.500 align:middle line:84%
as 80% to 90%, which
is as good as you're

00:42:04.500 --> 00:42:07.540 align:middle line:84%
going to get in
pharmacology, OK?

00:42:07.540 --> 00:42:08.040 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:11.115 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: What is the difference
in this placebo research

00:42:11.115 --> 00:42:14.580 align:middle line:84%
that shows us, we
go from maybe 10%

00:42:14.580 --> 00:42:18.950 align:middle line:84%
to maybe 90%, but
your perception?

00:42:18.950 --> 00:42:23.080 align:middle line:84%
Your perception is looking
at this gamut of events,

00:42:23.080 --> 00:42:26.220 align:middle line:84%
and the plain white
pill is cheap.

00:42:26.220 --> 00:42:29.672 align:middle line:84%
But as we moved up the line,
there's a perception of value.

00:42:29.672 --> 00:42:30.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, yes.

00:42:30.380 --> 00:42:33.710 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And that perception
of value increases what?

00:42:33.710 --> 00:42:35.600 align:middle line:90%
The strength of the placebo.

00:42:35.600 --> 00:42:36.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, interesting.

00:42:36.600 --> 00:42:40.510 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And I
respond by my body

00:42:40.510 --> 00:42:43.960 align:middle line:84%
healing itself as a
result of that placebo,

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:45.990 align:middle line:90%
in a very real way.

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:52.220 align:middle line:84%
So that's the kind of power
that our beliefs, our mentation,

00:42:52.220 --> 00:42:53.510 align:middle line:90%
have over our lives.

00:42:53.510 --> 00:42:55.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And if you were to
tell that person that was just

00:42:55.080 --> 00:42:57.190 align:middle line:84%
a placebo, they would
revert all of the healing.

00:42:57.190 --> 00:42:58.148 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Well, indeed.

00:42:58.148 --> 00:43:00.910 align:middle line:84%
You know, there is
a very famous case

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:06.310 align:middle line:84%
of precisely that, where an
individual dying of cancer,

00:43:06.310 --> 00:43:10.490 align:middle line:84%
on his last leg, seeks
out a physician who

00:43:10.490 --> 00:43:12.320 align:middle line:90%
is in a drug trial.

00:43:12.320 --> 00:43:15.870 align:middle line:84%
Begs, basically to get
into that drug trial.

00:43:15.870 --> 00:43:17.890 align:middle line:90%
What is there for him to lose?

00:43:17.890 --> 00:43:22.730 align:middle line:84%
So the physician admits him
to the hospital on a Friday,

00:43:22.730 --> 00:43:24.410 align:middle line:84%
goes away for the
weekend, doesn't

00:43:24.410 --> 00:43:27.170 align:middle line:84%
expect he'll still
be alive come Monday.

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:31.790 align:middle line:84%
But he enters the drug trial
and come Monday, he's improving.

00:43:31.790 --> 00:43:35.690 align:middle line:84%
And so they continue
the treatment protocol.

00:43:35.690 --> 00:43:39.030 align:middle line:84%
Sure enough, he's up and
out of the hospital, healed.

00:43:39.030 --> 00:43:42.949 align:middle line:84%
And then the published effects
of the drug trial come out--

00:43:42.949 --> 00:43:43.990 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It was a placebo.

00:43:43.990 --> 00:43:46.220 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And we
learn, no, we learn

00:43:46.220 --> 00:43:48.770 align:middle line:90%
that the drug was ineffective.

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:49.270 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:43:49.270 --> 00:43:54.460 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: And so, bang, he
has a re-onset of the cancer.

00:43:54.460 --> 00:43:56.980 align:middle line:84%
But he sees the physician,
who's smart enough

00:43:56.980 --> 00:44:00.680 align:middle line:84%
to figure out that the
mind is involved here.

00:44:00.680 --> 00:44:02.710 align:middle line:84%
So the physician
says, you know, I've

00:44:02.710 --> 00:44:05.430 align:middle line:84%
got a heavier dose of
that in a new trial.

00:44:05.430 --> 00:44:08.580 align:middle line:84%
And what we're getting is
just incredible results.

00:44:08.580 --> 00:44:10.470 align:middle line:90%
Let me put you on that.

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:11.710 align:middle line:90%
He does.

00:44:11.710 --> 00:44:14.880 align:middle line:84%
The patient recovers again,
goes into complete remission.

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:15.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:44:15.510 --> 00:44:18.080 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: Dances, goes home.

00:44:18.080 --> 00:44:21.250 align:middle line:84%
A couple of months later,
major article appears,

00:44:21.250 --> 00:44:24.620 align:middle line:84%
and this patient
finds the article.

00:44:24.620 --> 00:44:27.090 align:middle line:84%
And the article says
this particular drug

00:44:27.090 --> 00:44:30.496 align:middle line:84%
has zero effect, at
any dosage level,

00:44:30.496 --> 00:44:31.620 align:middle line:90%
on the treatment of cancer.

00:44:31.620 --> 00:44:33.750 align:middle line:84%
And the patient's dead
in just a few days.

00:44:33.750 --> 00:44:36.600 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This would all
explain why you won the,

00:44:36.600 --> 00:44:39.480 align:middle line:84%
was it, the 2005
International Peace Prize

00:44:39.480 --> 00:44:44.140 align:middle line:84%
by the International Cultural
Convention in the United States

00:44:44.140 --> 00:44:48.640 align:middle line:84%
for your work on teaching
self responsibility.

00:44:48.640 --> 00:44:50.250 align:middle line:84%
>>TAYLOR: My
message is about how

00:44:50.250 --> 00:44:52.050 align:middle line:90%
you become a better human being.

00:44:52.050 --> 00:44:53.510 align:middle line:84%
And that better
human being doesn't

00:44:53.510 --> 00:44:56.110 align:middle line:84%
require you to go
out and buy anything.

00:44:56.110 --> 00:45:00.000 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't require you
to do a whole lot more

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.780 align:middle line:84%
than to sit down,
become centered,

00:45:02.780 --> 00:45:06.140 align:middle line:84%
get still with yourself,
and learn who you are.

00:45:06.140 --> 00:45:07.930 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Back to the
authentic truth, yes.

00:45:07.930 --> 00:45:08.280 align:middle line:90%
>>TAYLOR: That's right.

00:45:08.280 --> 00:45:09.680 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's exactly
what we talked about.

00:45:09.680 --> 00:45:11.770 align:middle line:84%
Well there's, as we know,
Eldon's a great storyteller.

00:45:11.770 --> 00:45:13.260 align:middle line:84%
So I want you take
a look at this video

00:45:13.260 --> 00:45:15.134 align:middle line:84%
of telling a really
wonderful teaching story.

00:45:15.134 --> 00:45:15.941 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:45:15.941 --> 00:45:18.296 align:middle line:90%
